Mr. FLINT. I think there is a great deal of weight in what the member for Assiniboia (Mr. Davin) says. I think that it is almost too hard upon sheriffs to compel them to appoint deputies. I should think it would be better that each sheriff should appoint a deputy, leav- ing it to be inferred that the powers of the deputy are the usual powers of a deputy under the common law, or under any law of this Parliament.
